words: Um, what came out of my wedding,
actually, going back to my wedding, was the, um, I really love paper
products and the printing process. And, um, I came
across this... these beautiful invitations that were letter pressed, which is a, um,
antique style of printing, um, with moveable type
and a letter press that can function without electricity.
And so, my husband got me a a little mini press for, as his wedding gift to
me, ah, which was very sweet. And so, I got hooked and, um, when we were living in San Diego,
I was taking all these letterpress classes at this, um, place called
Bay Park Press and I loved the teacher, I loved the classes, I felt a really
strong connection to the whole process of making the art. And,
um, one of
the last projects we made, she... that... our teacher asked us to do
before I was going to move, actually back up here, is she wanted us
to make a book. And, I wanted to make it really, really special
and so, my husband actually wrote the text and I designed the layout of the pages
and set all of the type, each individual piece of type cause each letter,
um, and picked up colors,
did all, the whole art direction of the book and printed all the pages.
I think I made enough pages for, I believe, twenty copies.
And, um, there were about, I think, twenty pages in all.
And, um,
I went, did all the printing and it was a little bit crazy cause it turned
out to be a really huge project, um, more than I could handle at the time, but I wanted to finish it before
I left because all of my type was set and I didn't want to mess up anything.
I didn't want to leave the project unfinished after I moved up here because I knew I would never get
it done. Um, and so, I, um,
finished the printing and I knew I wanted to bind the book.
And, she taught us also how to bind the book and, and get it all ready to go to bind the
book up here. And then, she asked that I send two copies down
to her and she could put it in her display area where she has like a gallery and,
um, maybe somebody would buy it. And so, I did go ahead
and bind about five copies and, um, I signed them and numbered them
because they were an edition of twenty and I was very, very happy with how it turned
out, the color, the paper, I was just thrilled that I had accomplished, it was a really big
project and I had never really done anything like this before in terms of art and creativity
and, um, at most, I just studied art. I was an art history
major so it was really fun to apply the art, the creativity
